WEBVTT

00:06.548 --> 00:09.510
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:09.510 --> 00:16.683
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:16.683 --> 00:18.101
‐ My name is Cameron Alarcio.

00:18.101 --> 00:20.854
I'm 31 years old,
and I'm a full‐time teacher.

00:20.854 --> 00:22.564
<i>I tell my students</i>

00:22.564 --> 00:24.608
<i>that they can really achieve</i>
<i>anything they want.</i>

00:24.608 --> 00:26.735
<i>So I want to do</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire"</i>

00:26.735 --> 00:30.280
to prove to myself
that I am able to compete

00:30.280 --> 00:31.615
with some of the best
bladesmiths out there.

00:33.200 --> 00:34.826
<i>‐ My name</i>
<i>is Justin Kowspiachi.</i>

00:34.826 --> 00:36.537
<i>I live</i>
<i>in Salt Lake City, Utah.</i>

00:36.537 --> 00:39.248
I'm about to make a knife
for three expert judges.

00:39.248 --> 00:41.375
<i>Ben Abbott, he has, like, eyes</i>
<i>like a hawk,</i>

00:41.375 --> 00:43.293
so he'll be able to find
any flaws I make.

00:43.293 --> 00:45.712
David Baker has a moustache
that's just glorious,

00:45.712 --> 00:47.881
so you know that he knows
what he's talking about.

00:47.881 --> 00:50.384
And, like, Doug Marcaida,
he's just dangerous, man.

00:50.384 --> 00:53.053
That makes me feel
pretty nervous.

00:53.053 --> 00:56.265
‐ My name is Nic Overton.
I'm 22 years old.

00:56.265 --> 00:58.058
<i>There was a scouting program</i>
<i>through my church,</i>

00:58.058 --> 00:59.393
<i>and we camp out one summer,</i>

00:59.393 --> 01:00.394
<i>and they had</i>
<i>a blacksmith shop.</i>

01:00.394 --> 01:01.728
<i>Made my first knife there,</i>

01:01.728 --> 01:03.605
and it's been
a snowball effect ever since.

01:03.605 --> 01:06.358
<i>And now the same shop</i>
<i>that they taught me in</i>

01:06.358 --> 01:08.777
<i>is now partly my shop,</i>

01:08.777 --> 01:10.904
and I get to teach
the Scouts there as well.

01:10.904 --> 01:12.072
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:12.072 --> 01:13.490
<i>‐ My name is Matt Presti.</i>

01:13.490 --> 01:15.075
<i>I'm from</i>
<i>Union Bridge, Maryland.</i>

01:15.075 --> 01:17.828
I am a tattoo artist by trade.

01:17.828 --> 01:21.623
<i>Tattoos and bladesmithing</i>
<i>kind of go hand‐in‐hand</i>

01:21.623 --> 01:24.501
<i>because of the design aspect</i>
<i>and being able</i>

01:24.501 --> 01:28.171
to create something out of it
that makes people happy.

01:28.171 --> 01:32.092
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:32.092 --> 01:34.761
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:34.761 --> 01:36.430
You're here to engage
in three rounds

01:36.430 --> 01:38.640
of timed edged weapon
making competition

01:38.640 --> 01:41.268
specifically designed to test
every aspect of your skills

01:41.268 --> 01:43.353
in front of our panel
of expert judges

01:43.353 --> 01:44.855
who will tell us which of you
is our next

01:44.855 --> 01:46.440
"Forged in Fire" Champion,

01:46.440 --> 01:49.651
walking out of this
forge with a check for $10,000.

01:49.651 --> 01:51.445
Let's go ahead
and meet your judges now.

01:51.445 --> 01:53.447
Up first, two‐time
"Forged in Fire" champion

01:53.447 --> 01:54.990
Ben Abbott.

01:54.990 --> 01:58.285
Historic Weapons re‐creation
specialist, David Baker.

01:58.285 --> 02:01.121
And last, edged and impact
weapons specialist,

02:01.121 --> 02:03.123
Doug Marcaida.

02:03.123 --> 02:06.418
Gentlemen, my favorite
activities are camping,

02:06.418 --> 02:08.670
pool parties, and picnics.

02:08.670 --> 02:10.339
But, you can't have
any of those things

02:10.339 --> 02:12.466
without a barbecue.

02:12.466 --> 02:14.301
In this first round
of competition,

02:14.301 --> 02:16.970
you'll have to harvest steel
from this barbecue

02:16.970 --> 02:18.388
and forge camp knives.

02:20.974 --> 02:22.517
<i>Dating back to the 1800s,</i>

02:22.517 --> 02:24.811
<i>the camp knife was a staple</i>
<i>for the mountain men</i>

02:24.811 --> 02:26.480
<i>and fur traders</i>
<i>who first used them</i>

02:26.480 --> 02:28.649
<i>to skin and butcher</i>
<i>the animals they caught.</i>

02:28.649 --> 02:30.525
<i>These all‐purpose knives</i>
<i>typically featured</i>

02:30.525 --> 02:33.320
<i>a robust spine</i>
<i>that tapers to a fine edge,</i>

02:33.320 --> 02:36.990
<i>making them suitable</i>
<i>for a variety of tasks.</i>

02:36.990 --> 02:38.659
<i>You'll have to make</i>
<i>a camp knife</i>

02:38.659 --> 02:41.203
<i>between ten and 12 inches</i>
<i>in length,</i>

02:41.203 --> 02:42.996
as measured from the tip
to the plunge grind.

02:42.996 --> 02:44.748
And one other thing:

02:44.748 --> 02:49.252
Your blades must also include
an operational bottle opener.

02:49.252 --> 02:52.089
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:52.089 --> 02:54.508
Some of this is mild.
Some of this is high carbon.

02:54.508 --> 02:56.009
It's up to your skill set

02:56.009 --> 02:59.721
to determine what's what
and forge your blade.

02:59.721 --> 03:02.766
‐ A normal barbecue for me
is some surf‐and‐turf,

03:02.766 --> 03:04.685
<i>definitely some beers.</i>

03:04.685 --> 03:09.064
<i>Disassembling a barbecue</i>
<i>and making blades out of it,</i>

03:09.064 --> 03:11.650
definitely not what I think of
when I think of a barbecue.

03:14.194 --> 03:16.780
‐ If you make it to the second
round of this competition,

03:16.780 --> 03:19.074
you'll have an opportunity to
attach handles to those blades,

03:19.074 --> 03:21.076
turning them into
fully functional weapons

03:21.076 --> 03:23.412
that will be tested
for strength and durability

03:23.412 --> 03:25.080
in a firewood chop,

03:25.080 --> 03:28.166
and for edge retention
in a pork shoulder slice.

03:29.751 --> 03:31.044
Good luck, bladesmiths.

03:31.044 --> 03:34.881
Your time starts...

03:34.881 --> 03:36.049
now.

03:36.049 --> 03:38.885
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:38.885 --> 03:40.720
Well, cheers, gentlemen.

03:40.720 --> 03:43.265
‐ Yee‐haw.

03:43.265 --> 03:44.808
‐ Here in this first round
of competition,

03:44.808 --> 03:45.976
each one of these guys
has to make

03:45.976 --> 03:48.478
a ten to 12‐inch camp knife.

03:48.478 --> 03:53.817
We're looking for parallel flat
sides going to a drop point.

03:53.817 --> 03:56.570
‐ Yeah. There's one other thing
that's really important,

03:56.570 --> 03:58.405
and I hope these smiths
take it into account,

03:58.405 --> 04:00.740
is the placement
of that bottle opener.

04:00.740 --> 04:03.076
Ideally, right at the back
of the tang

04:03.076 --> 04:04.703
as if it's never in your way.

04:04.703 --> 04:05.954
‐ Okay.

04:05.954 --> 04:08.248
‐ Immediately,
I look at the spit

04:08.248 --> 04:11.751
and that looks to me like it's
gonna be high carbon steel.

04:11.751 --> 04:14.588
Put it down‐‐put it down
a little lower past this.

04:14.588 --> 04:17.591
‐ Now it's up to their own
skill set to determine

04:17.591 --> 04:20.469
what's mild steel,
what's high carbon steel,

04:20.469 --> 04:24.514
and how to assemble
those things into a billet.

04:24.514 --> 04:26.433
‐ Well, let's test some of
these pieces of steel here.

04:26.433 --> 04:28.435
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:28.435 --> 04:30.479
‐ You could do a smart test.

04:30.479 --> 04:34.441
But the sure‐fire way is take
a piece of steel, get it hot,

04:34.441 --> 04:35.984
quench it, and check it.

04:35.984 --> 04:38.612
<i>‐ I chop off a little piece</i>
<i>of that spit.</i>

04:38.612 --> 04:40.530
<i>I throw it in the forge</i>
<i>immediately to see</i>

04:40.530 --> 04:42.324
if I can get it up to temp,

04:42.324 --> 04:44.367
quench it,
and check to see if it's hard.

04:47.287 --> 04:48.955
‐ There are some things
that anybody

04:48.955 --> 04:51.625
who kind of
hangs around metal knows

04:51.625 --> 04:54.586
is not high carbon steel,
like the oil drums,

04:54.586 --> 04:56.838
the hollow tube,
the square tube underneath.

04:56.838 --> 05:00.300
‐ Mind if I borrow that?
‐ By all means, sir.

05:00.300 --> 05:01.635
‐ I'm gonna start
with the tines

05:01.635 --> 05:03.553
and I'm gonna spark test it.

05:03.553 --> 05:05.972
‐ The sparks don't look bad.

05:05.972 --> 05:07.474
<i>‐ Tines seem to be</i>
<i>throwing off sparks.</i>

05:07.474 --> 05:09.810
It tells me it's carbon steel.

05:09.810 --> 05:13.480
‐ As soon as that piece
gets up to heat, I quench it.

05:13.480 --> 05:16.650
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:18.151 --> 05:20.529
No.

05:20.529 --> 05:22.531
The file does not skate at all,

05:22.531 --> 05:25.242
which means that
that's not hardenable steel.

05:25.242 --> 05:27.661
I need to think of a Plan B.
[snaps] Ding.

05:27.661 --> 05:28.787
Light bulb goes off.

05:28.787 --> 05:30.831
<i>Throw it in a canister.</i>

05:30.831 --> 05:33.124
<i>I'm just gonna</i>
<i>cut up pieces of steel,</i>

05:33.124 --> 05:34.793
<i>and I'm going to throw</i>
<i>all of it into a canister</i>

05:34.793 --> 05:37.045
<i>with some 1095,</i>
<i>and that will hopefully</i>

05:37.045 --> 05:38.755
give me a solid billet.

05:38.755 --> 05:40.549
‐ If you're not sure
what's in there,

05:40.549 --> 05:42.175
I'd go with amateur Damascus.

05:42.175 --> 05:43.885
‐ You've got a 1095
powder steel

05:43.885 --> 05:45.846
that you know
you can mix in‐between.

05:48.098 --> 05:49.933
‐ I can't figure out
what's high carbon or not

05:49.933 --> 05:52.602
and it don't matter
if it's not high carbon

05:52.602 --> 05:56.022
<i>as long as your edge</i>
<i>is good with the 1095 powder.</i>

05:56.022 --> 05:58.066
Normally
when I go to a barbecue,

05:58.066 --> 05:59.693
<i>we're cooking steak.</i>

05:59.693 --> 06:01.903
So I think this is going to be
the most intense barbecue

06:01.903 --> 06:02.946
that I've ever been to.

06:02.946 --> 06:06.032
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:06.032 --> 06:08.869
<i>‐ Of course, the spikes</i>
<i>are not enough to make</i>

06:08.869 --> 06:11.204
and meet the parameters of
the knives we're gonna build,

06:11.204 --> 06:13.957
so I'm going to do a canister.

06:13.957 --> 06:16.418
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:16.418 --> 06:19.546
<i>I want to do this competition</i>
<i>for my mom.</i>

06:19.546 --> 06:23.884
She was diagnosed with cancer
and passed away.

06:23.884 --> 06:25.886
<i>We used to watch</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire" together</i>

06:25.886 --> 06:27.762
and she would tell me,
"Hey, can you do that?

06:27.762 --> 06:29.472
Can you do that?"
So I'm doing this for her.

06:32.058 --> 06:34.144
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:34.144 --> 06:35.896
‐ The first thing I do
is cut off

06:35.896 --> 06:38.732
<i>a piece of</i>
<i>the big, round spit.</i>

06:38.732 --> 06:40.859
<i>I think it has the mass</i>
<i>to produce</i>

06:40.859 --> 06:44.070
the size of knife
that they're looking for.

06:44.070 --> 06:46.114
‐ Matt, he's drawing out
a piece of steel.

06:46.114 --> 06:48.700
I don't know if that's
high carbon or mild.

06:48.700 --> 06:51.786
<i>‐ I do not know what kind</i>
<i>of steel the spit is.</i>

06:51.786 --> 06:53.496
I just assume

06:53.496 --> 06:56.207
that the bigger round bar's
a higher carbon steel.

06:57.917 --> 07:02.047
‐ Bladesmiths,
one hour has elapsed.

07:02.047 --> 07:04.799
‐ So I take my canister
over to the press.

07:04.799 --> 07:07.761
Rather than getting a straight
square, which is, you know,

07:07.761 --> 07:09.763
what you want
when you're doing a canister...

07:09.763 --> 07:11.473
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:11.473 --> 07:13.767
I'm getting this diamond shape

07:13.767 --> 07:15.769
that's folding over
on one side.

07:15.769 --> 07:17.604
‐ There just wasn't enough
to press.

07:17.604 --> 07:19.439
The presses that we have,
have sort of

07:19.439 --> 07:20.940
a secondary pressure

07:20.940 --> 07:23.818
that kicks in
and really compresses.

07:23.818 --> 07:25.779
So unless you hit that,
you're not gonna get

07:25.779 --> 07:28.031
the compression you need
to get that forge weld.

07:28.031 --> 07:30.033
<i>‐ But I have to just</i>
<i>get it hot again.</i>

07:30.033 --> 07:31.785
<i>Squeeze it so that I can</i>

07:31.785 --> 07:37.290
hopefully get a completely
homogenous piece in there.

07:37.290 --> 07:38.958
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:38.958 --> 07:42.087
‐ Once my billet is up
to the right temperature,

07:42.087 --> 07:44.214
I'm gonna very
gently squeeze it.

07:44.214 --> 07:46.049
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:46.049 --> 07:47.634
Just think of it
as like a snowball.

07:47.634 --> 07:49.803
You push too hard,
it's gonna go everywhere.

07:49.803 --> 07:51.680
You slowly pack it both ways,

07:51.680 --> 07:53.848
<i>and then when you finally get</i>
<i>to where you need to be,</i>

07:53.848 --> 07:55.350
<i>you can really get</i>
<i>some force on it.</i>

07:55.350 --> 07:57.435
<i>But the first, you need</i>
<i>to really take some baby steps</i>

07:57.435 --> 07:59.437
to getting that weld set.

08:00.480 --> 08:02.982
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:02.982 --> 08:06.569
<i>‐ I'm over at big blue.</i>
<i>I'm drawing it out.</i>

08:06.569 --> 08:08.905
Once I get it to kind of
the size and the parameters

08:08.905 --> 08:10.156
that I want it to,

08:10.156 --> 08:11.825
I can start doing
some hand hammering.

08:11.825 --> 08:14.202
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:14.202 --> 08:17.789
‐ Matt's got a wood block.
<i>‐ So I brought with me</i>

08:17.789 --> 08:19.582
what I like
to call a schwocker.

08:19.582 --> 08:23.002
It's basically a wooden club,
and I schwock away.

08:23.002 --> 08:24.045
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:24.045 --> 08:25.422
‐ People have used a wood block

08:25.422 --> 08:27.298
to straighten
without deforming,

08:27.298 --> 08:29.008
without leaving dents.
‐ Okay.

08:29.008 --> 08:32.095
‐ Normally, I don't have time
constraints like this,

08:32.095 --> 08:34.556
so the sooner I can get
this fit into a knife shape,

08:34.556 --> 08:36.850
the better.

08:36.850 --> 08:38.852
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:38.852 --> 08:41.187
‐ It's now or never.
I got to get this welded.

08:41.187 --> 08:44.774
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:44.774 --> 08:46.901
Ah, come on, man.

08:46.901 --> 08:49.404
‐ What happens to the canister?

08:49.404 --> 08:51.197
<i>‐ Big, old gap in there.</i>

08:51.197 --> 08:52.991
<i>Oh, this is bad.</i>

08:52.991 --> 08:54.284
[bleep].

08:54.284 --> 08:55.577
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:55.577 --> 08:57.912
<i>‐ As I peel off the canister,</i>

08:57.912 --> 09:02.042
I am just hoping
that I have a solid weld.

09:02.042 --> 09:05.628
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:05.628 --> 09:08.131
‐ Oh, no! Oh!

09:08.131 --> 09:10.550
‐ What? What?
‐ Wow.

09:10.550 --> 09:13.219
I dropped it when I was
grinding it and it split on me.

09:13.219 --> 09:16.264
‐ He's inspecting
the inner contents

09:16.264 --> 09:18.725
to see if they welded up,
and he doesn't look happy.

09:18.725 --> 09:21.227
‐ Again, when he came off
the press,

09:21.227 --> 09:23.438
it didn't look like
he'd reduced that can much.

09:23.438 --> 09:25.231
But he might not
have pressed it down.

09:25.231 --> 09:27.067
<i>‐ This is unusable steel.</i>

09:27.067 --> 09:28.902
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:28.902 --> 09:30.904
‐ I can try to salvage
this canister,

09:30.904 --> 09:34.074
<i>but there's probably forge</i>
<i>scale building up in there.</i>

09:34.074 --> 09:35.992
No, there's no point
in chasing it.

09:36.743 --> 09:38.661
‐ I gotta start over.
I can't use any of this steel.

09:41.164 --> 09:45.043
‐ Cameron and Just
‐ Cameron restarting a new can.

09:45.043 --> 09:46.753
It's not a lot of time.

09:46.753 --> 09:48.254
‐ I think I'll adjust it.

09:48.254 --> 09:51.257
‐ I think he's thinking about
what to do next.

09:51.257 --> 09:52.217
‐ I have to start over.

09:52.217 --> 09:53.843
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:53.843 --> 09:57.263
Now I'm moving on
to that big chunk of spit.

09:57.263 --> 09:59.015
I'm just taking the best guess
on what I know

09:59.015 --> 10:00.975
I can at least get
a knife‐shaped object out of.

10:00.975 --> 10:04.896
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:04.896 --> 10:06.481
‐ I cut off pieces
of the grate.

10:06.481 --> 10:08.650
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:08.650 --> 10:10.443
All right, round two.
Here we go.

10:10.443 --> 10:12.362
I know that
I'm up against the clock

10:12.362 --> 10:13.988
<i>and it's gonna be tight.</i>

10:13.988 --> 10:15.156
<i>It's gonna come down</i>
<i>to the wire,</i>

10:15.156 --> 10:17.075
but I never give up.

10:17.909 --> 10:21.287
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:21.287 --> 10:25.125
‐ We got Nic trying to bang
a billet out of a hot can.

10:25.125 --> 10:26.167
It's not working out for him.

10:26.167 --> 10:27.710
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:27.710 --> 10:29.129
<i>‐ It is very difficult.</i>

10:29.129 --> 10:30.839
<i>I'm spending way too much time</i>

10:30.839 --> 10:32.757
when I need
to be shaping the steel.

10:32.757 --> 10:35.468
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:35.468 --> 10:37.470
Luckily, the can
finally comes off.

10:37.470 --> 10:38.596
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:38.596 --> 10:41.599
Whoo!
‐ There we go.

10:41.599 --> 10:43.309
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:43.309 --> 10:45.019
<i>‐ So I've got</i>
<i>my blade to shape.</i>

10:45.019 --> 10:48.398
So the plan is putting
this bottle opener

10:48.398 --> 10:52.235
in the front of the blade,
kind of like a gut hook.

10:52.235 --> 10:55.280
‐ We've seen those gut hooks
to be stress risers

10:55.280 --> 10:57.240
and make the blades crack.

10:57.240 --> 11:00.243
<i>‐ Putting a bottle opener</i>
<i>in the wrong place</i>

11:00.243 --> 11:02.078
<i>could weaken the blade,</i>

11:02.078 --> 11:04.330
but I think my blade
is coming along really well.

11:05.665 --> 11:07.584
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:07.584 --> 11:08.585
<i>‐ I've never put</i>
<i>a bottle opener</i>

11:08.585 --> 11:09.878
<i>in a blade before.</i>

11:09.878 --> 11:11.254
<i>I'm thinking</i>
<i>I'm gonna put a ring</i>

11:11.254 --> 11:13.006
<i>at the back end of the knife.</i>

11:13.006 --> 11:15.675
I think that swell will help
keep the knife in your hand

11:15.675 --> 11:18.511
<i>and just right up on the blade</i>
<i>in case you have to baton it</i>

11:18.511 --> 11:19.888
and you're not gonna
cut yourself

11:19.888 --> 11:21.306
when you're opening your beer

11:21.306 --> 11:22.765
<i>when you're camping</i>
<i>and fishing, right?</i>

11:22.765 --> 11:24.517
‐ Looks like Justin was able
to quickly forge out

11:24.517 --> 11:26.227
a blade with his monosteel.

11:26.227 --> 11:29.439
And Cameron's still working
on his second can.

11:29.439 --> 11:30.356
‐ Yeah.
‐ He's still got

11:30.356 --> 11:32.192
a long ways to go.

11:32.192 --> 11:34.819
‐ 60 minutes remaining
in the round.

11:34.819 --> 11:36.487
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:36.487 --> 11:38.698
<i>‐ I got my bottle opener</i>
<i>pretty much where I want it.</i>

11:38.698 --> 11:40.867
<i>Hopefully it can actually</i>
<i>open a bottle.</i>

11:40.867 --> 11:42.035
We gotta heat‐treat
this thing.

11:42.035 --> 11:46.706
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:46.706 --> 11:48.124
‐ Nic's blade's
looking real nice.

11:48.124 --> 11:50.293
That's a nice camp knife shape.

11:50.293 --> 11:52.212
‐ My blade is fully hardened.

11:52.212 --> 11:54.547
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:54.547 --> 11:56.132
‐ Justin just quenched.

11:56.132 --> 11:58.760
‐ I'm just praying
to the gods of metal

11:58.760 --> 12:00.220
that this blade is gonna
come out hard.

12:00.220 --> 12:02.931
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:02.931 --> 12:03.890
And it's not hard.

12:03.890 --> 12:05.642
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:05.642 --> 12:07.894
<i>I think, well, maybe</i>
<i>I'm working with mild steel.</i>

12:07.894 --> 12:10.230
Well, if I don't have a hard
blade, I might get eliminated.

12:10.230 --> 12:12.232
I'm freaking out.

12:12.232 --> 12:14.651
I don't have time
to make a whole other blade.

12:14.651 --> 12:17.278
All I need to do
is have a high carbon edge.

12:17.278 --> 12:18.947
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:18.947 --> 12:20.073
<i>I'm just gonna</i>
<i>cut some pieces off this grate</i>

12:20.073 --> 12:21.908
and I'm gonna do a snap test.

12:21.908 --> 12:23.117
<i>I know if I hit</i>
<i>that son of a bitch</i>

12:23.117 --> 12:24.744
<i>with a hammer and it breaks,</i>

12:24.744 --> 12:26.746
that means it has carbon in it
and it got hard.

12:26.746 --> 12:28.414
And I could forge weld it
onto the edge.

12:28.414 --> 12:30.917
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:30.917 --> 12:32.919
‐ Broke it right off.
‐ Broke it right off.

12:32.919 --> 12:35.338
Now you know
that's hardened steel.

12:35.338 --> 12:37.632
‐ I'm kicking myself
for not doing this sooner.

12:37.632 --> 12:39.425
‐ You know what?
This is the Hail Mary

12:39.425 --> 12:40.551
before time runs out.

12:42.637 --> 12:44.389
20 minutes, bladesmiths.

12:44.389 --> 12:45.890
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:45.890 --> 12:47.809
<i>‐ I'm able to peel</i>
<i>my second canister off</i>

12:47.809 --> 12:49.310
and start forging it.

12:49.310 --> 12:52.814
‐ Cameron. Just so far
behind the power curve.

12:52.814 --> 12:55.149
<i>‐ I know that to meet</i>
<i>the parameters,</i>

12:55.149 --> 12:57.610
I still have to put
a bottle opener on this knife.

12:57.610 --> 12:59.362
‐ Cameron needs to work
very quickly

12:59.362 --> 13:02.657
because he still
has to quench that blade.

13:02.657 --> 13:04.617
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:04.617 --> 13:06.119
‐ I'm thinking I want
to do an edge quench.

13:06.119 --> 13:08.204
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:08.204 --> 13:10.164
I feel like it produces

13:10.164 --> 13:14.210
a stronger, more durable blade.

13:16.212 --> 13:18.089
I take a file to my edge

13:18.089 --> 13:22.302
and the file bites
into the edge immediately.

13:22.302 --> 13:25.388
<i>That means</i>
<i>it's not hard steel.</i>

13:25.388 --> 13:27.765
Time's running out,
and the only thing I can do

13:27.765 --> 13:29.434
is try another edge quench.

13:30.143 --> 13:32.729
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:32.729 --> 13:37.108
‐ Justin is perfectly shaping
that piece of high carbon steel

13:37.108 --> 13:39.027
to the edge of his blade.

13:39.027 --> 13:40.778
‐ I really do applaud the fact

13:40.778 --> 13:43.823
that he was in the middle
of that and found a way out.

13:43.823 --> 13:44.824
I like it.

13:44.824 --> 13:46.534
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:46.534 --> 13:48.119
<i>‐ Clock's ticking.</i>

13:48.119 --> 13:49.662
<i>I'm almost out of time.</i>

13:49.662 --> 13:52.498
The high carbon steel
on my edge needs to get hard.

13:52.498 --> 13:56.753
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:56.753 --> 13:58.171
‐ And here comes the file test.

13:59.881 --> 14:01.090
‐ [bleep] yeah, man,
it's hard.

14:03.342 --> 14:05.094
‐ Cameron still needs
to quench.

14:05.094 --> 14:07.513
And then Matt over here's
looking to quench again

14:07.513 --> 14:10.767
'cause his blade
isn't getting hard.

14:10.767 --> 14:12.602
One minute, bladesmiths!

14:12.602 --> 14:14.812
<i>‐ I'm keeping my eye</i>
<i>on the clock,</i>

14:14.812 --> 14:18.816
making sure I get this done
before the time runs out.

14:18.816 --> 14:22.737
‐ 30 seconds!
‐ It's the moment of truth.

14:22.737 --> 14:24.530
‐ One more, one more, one more.

14:24.530 --> 14:25.698
‐ You got enough,
you got enough, buddy.

14:25.698 --> 14:26.866
‐ Now!
‐ It's already‐‐

14:26.866 --> 14:28.117
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:28.117 --> 14:29.327
‐ Oh!
‐ Thank you.

14:29.327 --> 14:30.286
‐ There you go.
‐ You're good.

14:30.286 --> 14:35.249
‐ Five, four, three, two, one.

14:35.249 --> 14:37.710
Bladesmiths, shut down your
machines, drop your tools.

14:37.710 --> 14:40.713
This first round
of competition is over.

14:40.713 --> 14:44.383
[applause]

14:44.383 --> 14:46.177
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:46.177 --> 14:49.138
‐ This is a disaster that
looks nothing like a knife.

14:49.138 --> 14:51.057
<i>There is a little bit</i>
<i>of solace in the fact</i>

14:51.057 --> 14:54.936
that I actually have something
to turn in,

14:54.936 --> 14:57.396
rather than show up
empty‐handed.

15:01.192 --> 15:02.652
‐ All right, bladesmiths.

15:02.652 --> 15:04.946
Time has elapsed in this
first round of competition.

15:04.946 --> 15:06.781
The judges are anxious
to see what you're done

15:06.781 --> 15:08.324
with all that time
that was given to you.

15:08.324 --> 15:09.659
Cameron, you're up first.

15:09.659 --> 15:12.036
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:12.036 --> 15:13.746
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:13.746 --> 15:17.917
‐ There is a lot of work to do
to make this a viable knife.

15:17.917 --> 15:19.961
Biggest concern,
there are cracks

15:19.961 --> 15:23.005
that run all the way
over the blade and the spine.

15:23.005 --> 15:26.300
You do have the starting of
what will be a bottle opener.

15:26.300 --> 15:28.761
You can move forward.
It's gonna be a lot of work.

15:30.054 --> 15:31.264
‐ All right, Nic,
you're up next.

15:31.264 --> 15:32.807
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:32.807 --> 15:34.809
‐ Well, Nic, I love the shape
of this knife.

15:34.809 --> 15:36.602
The handle seems comfortable.

15:36.602 --> 15:38.938
A little bit narrow right here.

15:38.938 --> 15:40.690
This is where I'm always
most critical is where

15:40.690 --> 15:42.483
my point of finger goes.

15:42.483 --> 15:43.985
So when you go
to put a handle on this,

15:43.985 --> 15:45.403
I'd like you to just
pay attention to that spot

15:45.403 --> 15:46.445
just to be sure.

15:46.445 --> 15:48.197
Well done.
‐ Thank you.

15:48.197 --> 15:50.908
‐ All right, Justin, you're up.

15:50.908 --> 15:52.952
‐ All right, Justin.
You did it.

15:52.952 --> 15:54.954
You knew you had mild steel,

15:54.954 --> 15:58.583
but you acted on it, and you
were able to find a solution.

15:58.583 --> 16:00.209
I commend you
to not giving up,

16:00.209 --> 16:01.794
and presenting a blade

16:01.794 --> 16:03.504
that does meet the parameters
that we're looking for,

16:03.504 --> 16:05.548
and putting that hardened
edge on it.

16:05.548 --> 16:08.342
Good job, sir.
‐ Thank you.

16:08.342 --> 16:09.969
‐ All right, Matt. You're up.

16:11.137 --> 16:13.097
<i>‐ Matt, what steel did you use</i>
<i>for this knife?</i>

16:13.097 --> 16:15.057
‐ I used the spit.

16:15.057 --> 16:17.935
‐ Do you think that that was
high carbon steel?

16:17.935 --> 16:20.146
‐ Initially I did, yes.

16:20.146 --> 16:21.314
‐ I'm not sure it was,

16:21.314 --> 16:22.982
so I'm gonna test this
with a file.

16:22.982 --> 16:24.859
If it's hardened,
and hardenable steel,

16:24.859 --> 16:28.029
that file should skate off
as if I was rubbing on glass.

16:28.029 --> 16:29.655
If it bites in significantly,

16:29.655 --> 16:32.658
then I know that this wasn't,
in fact, hardenable steel.

16:32.658 --> 16:35.161
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:35.161 --> 16:36.787
‐ Hmm.
This is pretty deep, man.

16:36.787 --> 16:38.497
‐ All right.
‐ There's a notch right there.

16:38.497 --> 16:41.209
‐ I see it.

16:41.209 --> 16:44.545
Matt, big problem
with your blade, here.

16:44.545 --> 16:47.256
There is no high carbon steel
in that blade

16:47.256 --> 16:50.092
and therefore, you don't have
an edge that is hardenable.

16:50.092 --> 16:51.719
And, therefore,
you don't have a knife.

16:51.719 --> 16:53.179
For that reason,
you can't move forward

16:53.179 --> 16:54.222
in this competition.

16:54.222 --> 16:55.181
Come on forward, my friend.

16:55.181 --> 16:57.266
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:57.266 --> 16:59.936
‐ I had some inclinations
towards the end

16:59.936 --> 17:02.313
<i>that it was not</i>
<i>hardenable steel</i>

17:02.313 --> 17:05.441
and at that point,
it was too late.

17:05.441 --> 17:07.026
<i>If I would have gotten</i>
<i>hardened steel</i>

17:07.026 --> 17:08.402
<i>on the edge of the blade,</i>
<i>I feel like</i>

17:08.402 --> 17:09.695
it would have
tested very well.

17:09.695 --> 17:12.073
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:12.073 --> 17:13.699
‐ Congratulations, bladesmiths.

17:13.699 --> 17:16.202
You've made it to the second
round of this competition.

17:16.202 --> 17:17.662
Now that those blades
have been tempered,

17:17.662 --> 17:19.038
it's time to finish
those blades off

17:19.038 --> 17:20.498
by attaching handles to them

17:20.498 --> 17:22.625
using the range of materials
on top of that barrel.

17:22.625 --> 17:24.043
♪ ♪

17:24.043 --> 17:26.545
That is a stack
of hickory wood.

17:26.545 --> 17:29.298
You'll have just two hours in
which to complete your handles

17:29.298 --> 17:30.758
and address any flaws
and issues

17:30.758 --> 17:32.593
that were identified
in your blades for you.

17:32.593 --> 17:34.428
That's a lot of work.

17:34.428 --> 17:37.306
After, we'll be testing them
for strength and durability

17:37.306 --> 17:39.600
in a firewood shop,

17:39.600 --> 17:43.729
and for edge retention
in a ham shoulder slice.

17:43.729 --> 17:45.648
I remind you that after
your blades have been tested,

17:45.648 --> 17:48.234
one of you will be selected
to surrender your blade

17:48.234 --> 17:49.902
and leave The Forge.

17:49.902 --> 17:53.573
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your two hours starts...now.

17:53.573 --> 17:55.533
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:55.533 --> 17:57.034
‐ Is this the type of wood

17:57.034 --> 17:58.661
that you would want
to throw onto a knife?

17:58.661 --> 18:00.997
‐ Well, I mean, hickory,
if it's properly cured,

18:00.997 --> 18:02.456
yeah, absolutely.

18:02.456 --> 18:05.376
‐ I'm feeling pretty good
going into round two.

18:05.376 --> 18:09.088
<i>I grab a piece of G10 liner</i>
<i>to back that wood up</i>

18:09.088 --> 18:12.008
just in case there is
something wrong inside the wood

18:12.008 --> 18:13.634
that I don't know about.

18:13.634 --> 18:16.929
<i>This G10 will give it</i>
<i>a stronger structure.</i>

18:16.929 --> 18:18.973
I feel like my mom
is proud of me right now.

18:18.973 --> 18:20.766
<i>She always taught me</i>
<i>to take one more step</i>

18:20.766 --> 18:22.101
further than the rest.

18:22.101 --> 18:24.186
And to always try my best,

18:24.186 --> 18:27.398
and no matter what,
that's gonna be good enough.

18:28.608 --> 18:33.154
‐ Cameron is in survival mode.
He has a blank right now.

18:33.154 --> 18:35.031
<i>‐ I feel lucky to be</i>
<i>in round two.</i>

18:35.031 --> 18:38.993
My biggest concern is to grind
out all the cracks I can

18:38.993 --> 18:40.119
<i>so that they're gonna be</i>
<i>a problem</i>

18:40.119 --> 18:42.121
when it comes
to the actual testing.

18:43.956 --> 18:45.458
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:45.458 --> 18:47.918
‐ So all this is welded on
with a MIG welder,

18:47.918 --> 18:51.505
and it's ugly,
so I gotta fix that.

18:51.505 --> 18:54.175
‐ I wouldn't grind
that weld line too much.

18:54.175 --> 18:56.177
‐ As much as you want
to make it look pretty,

18:56.177 --> 18:58.137
you have to think
mechanical as well.

18:58.137 --> 19:01.015
‐ I know I have to be careful,
so I grind away at this weld.

19:01.015 --> 19:02.516
This high carbon
is just gonna fall off,

19:02.516 --> 19:05.019
<i>and no carbon steel,</i>
<i>no knife.</i>

19:05.019 --> 19:06.979
It's gone. Sayonara.

19:06.979 --> 19:09.899
‐ 60 minutes, bladesmiths.

19:09.899 --> 19:12.193
<i>‐ The judges addressed that</i>
<i>the choil here on this blade</i>

19:12.193 --> 19:13.527
was a little thin.

19:13.527 --> 19:16.072
So right now
I'm gonna put a bolster on

19:16.072 --> 19:18.366
and make that bolster
a little thicker.

19:18.366 --> 19:21.160
‐ Nic is making some bolsters
from some hardwood

19:21.160 --> 19:22.953
but he's going to butt up
this hickory too.

19:22.953 --> 19:24.413
‐ You know,
and that's what we want to see.

19:24.413 --> 19:26.832
It should be stout.

19:26.832 --> 19:28.334
It should be something
that holds up.

19:31.504 --> 19:33.172
‐ Oh, man.

19:33.172 --> 19:35.341
<i>The bolster snaps in half.</i>

19:35.341 --> 19:38.344
I'm only allowed two hours
to finish this handle.

19:38.344 --> 19:41.722
Every second counts,
so I scrap the bolster idea.

19:41.722 --> 19:43.265
<i>We're just gonna have to go</i>

19:43.265 --> 19:45.559
and glue these scales
completely onto this blade.

19:45.559 --> 19:48.562
‐ Nic's done exactly
what you asked him not to do.

19:48.562 --> 19:50.523
The neck of his handle

19:50.523 --> 19:52.942
is almost like
the circumference of a hot dog.

19:52.942 --> 19:54.318
‐ Yeah.
‐ It's really narrow,

19:54.318 --> 19:55.903
but we'll see
how that holds up.

19:57.363 --> 19:59.031
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:59.031 --> 20:01.242
<i>‐ There's still a little crack</i>
<i>on the spine,</i>

20:01.242 --> 20:03.244
<i>but I realize</i>
<i>I've already eaten into</i>

20:03.244 --> 20:05.287
<i>a whole lot of time.</i>

20:05.287 --> 20:08.416
<i>I attach my handle scales</i>
<i>as securely as possible,</i>

20:08.416 --> 20:10.209
and I know that I have to have

20:10.209 --> 20:12.378
a working
bottle opener on there.

20:12.378 --> 20:14.463
‐ I want to see how Cameron
figures out

20:14.463 --> 20:17.758
how to turn a round hole
into a bottle opener.

20:17.758 --> 20:19.719
<i>‐ I cut into the hole</i>
<i>that I made</i>

20:19.719 --> 20:22.179
<i>to allow kind of a pry bar</i>
<i>bottle opener</i>

20:22.179 --> 20:23.931
<i>at the tail of my knife.</i>

20:23.931 --> 20:25.433
‐ That should work.

20:27.560 --> 20:29.270
‐ Justin's scales
are roughly shaped.

20:29.270 --> 20:32.481
He's got some pins.
The holes are drilled down.

20:32.481 --> 20:35.317
‐ While my epoxy's drying,
I don't have time to wait.

20:35.317 --> 20:37.278
So, I'm starting
to shape this thing,

20:37.278 --> 20:40.865
Ah, son of a bitch.

20:40.865 --> 20:42.908
There's a little bit
of a crack right here,

20:42.908 --> 20:44.744
but I'm hoping
I can grind it out.

20:45.870 --> 20:47.496
Grinding the crack out.

20:47.496 --> 20:49.999
It's gonna limit me
and remove too much material,

20:49.999 --> 20:51.917
but it's the quickest
and easiest solution.

20:51.917 --> 20:54.044
And I don't got
a lot of time left.

20:55.171 --> 20:56.881
‐20 minutes, bladesmiths.

20:58.424 --> 21:00.801
‐ It's time to really hone
in that edge.

21:00.801 --> 21:02.595
<i>The performance test</i>
<i>for these knives</i>

21:02.595 --> 21:05.014
<i>are to chop</i>
<i>through a hickory log</i>

21:05.014 --> 21:08.017
<i>and hopefully hold up</i>
<i>to withstand the ham slice.</i>

21:08.893 --> 21:11.479
‐ Looks like
that's sharp enough.

21:11.479 --> 21:13.731
I ended up testing on my arm
hairs to see if it will shave,

21:13.731 --> 21:16.776
and ended up taking a whole lot
more than just my arm hair.

21:16.776 --> 21:18.152
Thank you.

21:18.152 --> 21:20.029
<i>It will cut.</i>

21:20.029 --> 21:21.489
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:21.489 --> 21:22.865
‐ If anybody's feeling

21:22.865 --> 21:24.950
the pressure
and crunch of the clock,

21:24.950 --> 21:27.203
it's got to be Cameron
at this point.

21:27.203 --> 21:28.621
<i>‐ I'm pretty worried.</i>

21:28.621 --> 21:31.165
I started with really
thick pieces of hickory,

21:31.165 --> 21:33.793
thinking that I'd be able to
grind them down very quickly.

21:33.793 --> 21:37.505
<i>But, unfortunately, I do not</i>
<i>have time to break the edges,</i>

21:37.505 --> 21:41.300
so there are hard corners
on the bottom of my handle

21:41.300 --> 21:43.969
which are gonna
come back to bite me.

21:43.969 --> 21:47.223
‐ Cameron's really racing
to finish here.

21:47.223 --> 21:49.058
Next to him,
it looks like Justin's

21:49.058 --> 21:51.727
just cleaning up his blade
as best he can.

21:51.727 --> 21:54.522
‐ I want to make sure
that it's sharp and strong.

21:54.522 --> 21:57.691
Is it gonna hold up?
Those welds are still great.

21:57.691 --> 22:02.571
‐ Five, four, three, two, one.

22:03.155 --> 22:05.991
Bladesmiths, shut down
you machines. Drop your tools.

22:05.991 --> 22:08.327
This second round
of competition is over.

22:08.327 --> 22:09.995
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:09.995 --> 22:13.123
<i>‐ I don't know if my blade's</i>
<i>gonna survive the test.</i>

22:13.123 --> 22:15.501
If those mid‐welds
for my high carbon edge

22:15.501 --> 22:16.836
aren't strong enough,

22:16.836 --> 22:17.837
<i>that whole edge</i>
<i>could just come off</i>

22:17.837 --> 22:20.256
and go flying across the room.

22:20.256 --> 22:22.258
‐ Bladesmiths, welcome
to the strength test.

22:22.258 --> 22:24.176
To test the strength
and durability of your blades

22:24.176 --> 22:26.053
as well as the overall
construction of your knives,

22:26.053 --> 22:28.222
I'll be chopping into firewood.

22:28.222 --> 22:30.391
But what's more fun
than chopping into firewood?

22:30.391 --> 22:32.184
Chopping into firewood on fire.

22:32.184 --> 22:33.811
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:33.811 --> 22:35.354
Remember,
this test is all about

22:35.354 --> 22:36.939
what happens to your weapons

22:36.939 --> 22:38.524
and not what happens
to the logs.

22:38.524 --> 22:39.859
Cameron, you're first.
Are you ready?

22:39.859 --> 22:41.360
‐ Yes, sir.

22:41.360 --> 22:43.028
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:43.028 --> 22:44.864
<i>What I'm most worried about</i>

22:44.864 --> 22:47.575
<i>is the small crack</i>
<i>on the spine.</i>

22:48.367 --> 22:51.078
And I'm worried that crack
may extend down

22:51.078 --> 22:53.706
through the length of my blade
and actually crack in half.

22:53.706 --> 22:53.873
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:57.126 --> 22:58.460
<i>‐ What I'm most worried about</i>

22:58.460 --> 23:01.171
<i>is the small crack</i>
<i>on the spine.</i>

23:01.171 --> 23:03.924
I'm thinking, please just
survive the first chop.

23:03.924 --> 23:10.890
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:16.437 --> 23:17.897
[exhales]

23:17.897 --> 23:20.107
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:20.107 --> 23:21.650
‐ Well, Cameron, man,

23:21.650 --> 23:23.152
you pulled a knife
out of that thing.

23:23.152 --> 23:26.071
Coming into this round,
it was extremely rough.

23:26.071 --> 23:28.115
Your edge held up fine.

23:28.115 --> 23:31.368
But the biggest thing is
the sharp corners right here.

23:31.368 --> 23:34.204
But what you did in two hours
from what you started with,

23:34.204 --> 23:37.041
it's miraculous.
‐ Thank you.

23:37.041 --> 23:38.959
‐ Justin, you're up next.
‐ Let's do it.

23:38.959 --> 23:40.878
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:40.878 --> 23:43.088
<i>My heart's thumping.</i>

23:43.088 --> 23:45.633
<i>My pulse is beating faster,</i>
<i>and I'm real concerned</i>

23:45.633 --> 23:47.927
that my edge
is just gonna come flying off.

23:47.927 --> 23:54.808
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:00.105 --> 24:02.524
Great. It didn't break.
[chuckles]

24:02.524 --> 24:04.193
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:04.193 --> 24:08.405
‐ Well, Justin, it held up.
And it took no damage.

24:08.405 --> 24:11.408
I don't see any glinting or
edge deformation of any kind,

24:11.408 --> 24:15.871
so all‐in‐all, well done.
‐ Thank you, sir.

24:15.871 --> 24:18.082
‐ Nic, you're up.
What are you thinking?

24:18.082 --> 24:20.209
‐ Not much of anything
right now.

24:20.209 --> 24:21.919
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:21.919 --> 24:23.879
<i>After watching</i>
<i>the other two guys,</i>

24:23.879 --> 24:25.839
<i>I'm just hoping I can survive.</i>

24:25.839 --> 24:27.841
That was a very brutal test,

24:27.841 --> 24:31.136
and I have no idea what's
going on inside my blade.

24:31.136 --> 24:32.972
But we'll see how it goes.

24:34.348 --> 24:41.271
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:43.524 --> 24:45.943
[exhales]

24:45.943 --> 24:47.486
‐ Good job, man.
‐ Oh, thanks.

24:47.486 --> 24:48.904
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:48.904 --> 24:51.949
‐ Well, Nic, I don't see
any issue that happened

24:51.949 --> 24:54.326
from this test
on this blade whatsoever.

24:54.326 --> 24:55.661
The handle is comfortable.

24:55.661 --> 24:57.579
And good to see
your tang junction held up

24:57.579 --> 24:58.789
without the bolster.

24:58.789 --> 25:00.207
Well done.
‐ Thank you.

25:00.207 --> 25:03.919
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:03.919 --> 25:05.421
‐ All right, bladesmiths.

25:05.421 --> 25:08.507
This is the sharpness test,
the pork shoulder slice.

25:08.507 --> 25:10.509
Unlike the strength test,
this is all about

25:10.509 --> 25:13.637
what your edge will do
to these pork shoulders.

25:13.637 --> 25:14.722
Cameron, you're up first.

25:14.722 --> 25:16.098
Are you ready?
‐ Yes, please.

25:16.098 --> 25:21.103
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:21.103 --> 25:23.355
‐ Since we asked you to do
a bottle opener,

25:23.355 --> 25:24.815
we have to test to see
if it will open up.

25:24.815 --> 25:26.859
And just to let you know,
it's root beer

25:26.859 --> 25:28.318
because we don't
beer and blade.

25:28.318 --> 25:30.029
[chuckling]

25:31.905 --> 25:38.829
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:47.796 --> 25:49.673
All right, Cameron, first up.

25:49.673 --> 25:51.592
Your bottle opener works.

25:51.592 --> 25:55.095
Your edge, it's not very sharp,
but it cuts.

25:55.095 --> 25:57.347
But that's a lot also to do
with the velocity

25:57.347 --> 26:00.350
I'm doing in chopping
through the meat right there.

26:00.350 --> 26:04.021
Whatever it is you've done,
your blade, sir, it will cut.

26:05.981 --> 26:07.274
All right, Justin,
it's your turn.

26:07.274 --> 26:08.776
Are you ready, sir?
‐ Oh, yeah, bud.

26:08.776 --> 26:15.616
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:25.584 --> 26:26.543
‐ Jeez.

26:28.170 --> 26:29.713
‐ All right, Justin.

26:29.713 --> 26:33.425
Your edge not only is sharp,
but look at what it did.

26:33.425 --> 26:35.552
It cut through bone.
It's a deep cutter.

26:36.178 --> 26:39.181
And, of course, I got a swig.

26:39.181 --> 26:42.059
Overall, sir, your blade,
it will cut.

26:42.059 --> 26:44.103
‐ Thank you.

26:44.103 --> 26:45.729
‐ Nic, your turn, sir.
You ready?

26:45.729 --> 26:47.314
‐ Let's do it.
‐ Let's do this.

26:47.314 --> 26:53.112
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:53.112 --> 26:55.405
I'm thirsty! And‐‐

26:55.405 --> 26:57.324
Ah!

26:57.324 --> 26:58.992
I guess I'm gonna
do this test thirsty.

26:58.992 --> 27:05.916
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:08.210 --> 27:10.796
‐ Nice.
‐ Thanks.

27:10.796 --> 27:12.131
‐ All right, Nic.

27:12.131 --> 27:14.675
It's very nice
to slice and dice.

27:14.675 --> 27:17.427
Nice slashes, nice deep cuts.

27:17.427 --> 27:19.721
Even cuts to the bone.

27:19.721 --> 27:21.557
But I'm still thirsty.

27:21.557 --> 27:24.351
Overall, sir, your blade,
it will cut.

27:24.351 --> 27:26.770
‐ Yes.

27:26.770 --> 27:28.272
‐ All right, gents, it's time

27:28.272 --> 27:30.607
for one of your bladesmiths
to leave The Forge.

27:30.607 --> 27:32.192
The bladesmith leaving
The Forge is...

27:32.192 --> 27:34.486
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:34.486 --> 27:36.113
Cameron.

27:36.113 --> 27:37.698
Your blade did not
make the cut.

27:37.698 --> 27:39.491
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:39.491 --> 27:42.119
‐ Cameron, your second round
comeback was really impressive,

27:42.119 --> 27:44.705
the fact that you got that
blade finished the way you did.

27:44.705 --> 27:46.290
But you ran out of time
before you truly

27:46.290 --> 27:48.625
got an edge on there
or finished that handle.

27:50.294 --> 27:52.504
‐ Cameron, you did a great job.

27:52.504 --> 27:54.923
But at this time, I need you
to please surrender your blade.

27:54.923 --> 27:56.425
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:56.425 --> 27:59.636
<i>‐ I'm proud that I never</i>
<i>really gave up.</i>

27:59.636 --> 28:01.054
‐ Good job, Cameron, seriously.
‐ Thanks, guys.

28:01.054 --> 28:02.806
I believe that I gave

28:02.806 --> 28:05.309
everything I had
this entire challenge.

28:05.309 --> 28:06.935
And I sure had a hell
of a time competing.

28:06.935 --> 28:10.439
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:10.439 --> 28:12.107
‐ Justin, Nic, congratulations.

28:12.107 --> 28:15.611
You fellows are in the final
round of this competition.

28:15.611 --> 28:17.237
Now we're sending you back
to your home forges

28:17.237 --> 28:19.948
to recreate this iconic weapon
from history.

28:19.948 --> 28:22.034
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:22.034 --> 28:24.411
A pair of Frankish
throwing axes.

28:24.411 --> 28:27.372
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:27.372 --> 28:29.833
<i>The Frankish throwing axe was</i>
<i>the deadly and iconic weapon</i>

28:29.833 --> 28:31.585
<i>of Germanic tribes</i>
<i>known as the Franks</i>

28:31.585 --> 28:32.961
<i>during the third century.</i>

28:32.961 --> 28:35.088
<i>Masters of</i>
<i>shock and awe combat,</i>

28:35.088 --> 28:37.299
<i>the Franks carried</i>
<i>multiple axes in battle,</i>

28:37.299 --> 28:38.800
<i>and they would throw them</i>
<i>at close range</i>

28:38.800 --> 28:40.969
<i>to break formation</i>
<i>and cause chaos.</i>

28:40.969 --> 28:43.555
<i>The axe's heavy blade</i>
<i>and razor‐sharp edge</i>

28:43.555 --> 28:45.307
<i>cut deep into enemy flesh,</i>

28:45.307 --> 28:48.226
<i>and was capable of damaging</i>
<i>armor and crushing bone.</i>

28:48.226 --> 28:50.145
<i>The axe's brutality</i>
<i>in the hands of the Franks</i>

28:50.145 --> 28:51.647
<i>is still prevalent in movies</i>

28:51.647 --> 28:54.232
<i>and can be seen</i>
<i>in the 2010 film, "Centurion."</i>

28:54.232 --> 28:55.233
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:55.233 --> 28:56.652
The length of the axe head

28:56.652 --> 28:58.820
must be between
six and seven inches.

28:58.820 --> 29:01.990
You must have an S‐shaped curve
to the top of your axe.

29:01.990 --> 29:03.784
You must have a hammer back.

29:03.784 --> 29:08.622
And you must have handles that
curve away from the axe's edge.

29:08.622 --> 29:09.831
<i>‐ I'm a little intimidated.</i>

29:09.831 --> 29:13.627
I've only made a handful
of axes/tomahawks.

29:13.627 --> 29:15.420
<i>It's not out of my element,</i>

29:15.420 --> 29:17.547
but it's going
to be a challenge.

29:17.547 --> 29:19.508
‐ You'll have just four days
at your home forges

29:19.508 --> 29:21.009
in which
to complete your weapons.

29:21.009 --> 29:23.178
At the end of those four days,
you will return

29:23.178 --> 29:25.722
to present your weapons
to our panel of expert judges.

29:25.722 --> 29:28.141
And after they've thoroughly
and brutally tested them,

29:28.141 --> 29:30.227
they'll declare one of you
the "Forge in Fire" Champion

29:30.227 --> 29:33.480
who leaves here
with a check for $10,000.

29:33.480 --> 29:35.232
Good luck.
We'll see you in four days.

29:35.232 --> 29:37.818
‐ Good luck, man.
‐ Good luck to you, man.

29:37.818 --> 29:40.112
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:40.112 --> 29:42.614
<i>It feels great</i>
<i>to be back home.</i>

29:42.614 --> 29:45.033
<i>I have to make a pair</i>
<i>of Frankish throwing axes.</i>

29:45.033 --> 29:46.535
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:46.535 --> 29:48.245
<i>There's a lot of subtle</i>
<i>curves to them,</i>

29:48.245 --> 29:49.955
<i>so it's going to be</i>
<i>a real challenge.</i>

29:49.955 --> 29:52.332
<i>I'm gonna take my piece</i>
<i>of mild steel.</i>

29:52.332 --> 29:54.418
I'm going to forge it out,
and then I'm gonna

29:54.418 --> 29:56.044
fold it over on itself

29:56.044 --> 29:57.504
<i>and then I'm gonna fit it</i>
<i>for a bit</i>

29:57.504 --> 29:59.131
<i>of high carbon steel</i>
<i>in the middle.</i>

29:59.131 --> 30:00.674
<i>I think that might work.</i>

30:00.674 --> 30:02.509
Mild steel doesn't like to weld

30:02.509 --> 30:04.845
at the heats
that carbon field does.

30:04.845 --> 30:07.347
Hopefully, she welds.

30:07.347 --> 30:09.850
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:09.850 --> 30:12.310
<i>‐ So I'm really excited.</i>
<i>We've made it to round three.</i>

30:12.310 --> 30:13.645
<i>I'm ready to get sweaty</i>

30:13.645 --> 30:15.689
and get some sparks
thrown on this thing.

30:15.689 --> 30:19.359
<i>So the plan today is I'm going</i>
<i>to take some 1018 mild steel.</i>

30:19.359 --> 30:21.236
We're gonna start
by drilling two holes,

30:21.236 --> 30:23.113
go in with a drift,

30:23.113 --> 30:26.158
chisel it out, start forming
our eye on both of these.

30:26.158 --> 30:30.328
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:30.328 --> 30:32.205
Looks like a good eye
right there.

30:32.205 --> 30:33.790
<i>It's time to really profile</i>
<i>this thing.</i>

30:33.790 --> 30:35.250
<i>So I'm taking it</i>
<i>to the power hammer.</i>

30:35.250 --> 30:36.334
The way they meet up
a lot easier.

30:36.334 --> 30:37.669
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:37.669 --> 30:39.379
I'll have
the profile forged out,

30:39.379 --> 30:40.839
have the eyes drifted.

30:40.839 --> 30:42.340
<i>I'm feeling pretty good</i>
<i>about day one,</i>

30:42.340 --> 30:44.051
<i>but we got</i>
<i>a whole lot more work to do.</i>

30:44.051 --> 30:46.303
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:46.303 --> 30:49.264
‐ It's the morning of day two,
and I'm pretty tired.

30:49.264 --> 30:51.683
<i>Yesterday I was able</i>
<i>to get both my axes</i>

30:51.683 --> 30:53.101
<i>forge welded together.</i>

30:53.101 --> 30:55.395
Now I just got to finish
drawing them out today.

30:55.395 --> 30:57.689
I wanna get that down to shape.

30:57.689 --> 30:58.982
And it looks like
it's staying to‐‐

30:58.982 --> 31:00.567
Oh, never mind.

31:00.567 --> 31:02.486
It is not staying together.

31:02.486 --> 31:06.615
I got a massive seam where that
forge weld is supposed to me.

31:06.615 --> 31:09.326
The bolt didn't take it
in the very back of this,

31:09.326 --> 31:12.287
<i>so I'm gonna try to forge out</i>
<i>this other head</i>

31:12.287 --> 31:13.914
<i>and I'm gonna try it away.</i>

31:13.914 --> 31:16.458
<i>It split apart,</i>
<i>it's no good, so‐‐</i>

31:16.458 --> 31:18.168
Don't like that [bleep].

31:18.168 --> 31:20.170
<i>Too thin to even</i>
<i>really forge weld it again.</i>

31:20.170 --> 31:20.921
<i>So I have to start over.</i>

31:23.715 --> 31:25.342
<i>I'm almost a quarter</i>
<i>of the way through,</i>

31:25.342 --> 31:27.511
<i>and I have to start over.</i>

31:27.511 --> 31:29.221
I don't know what these tests
are gonna be,

31:29.221 --> 31:30.722
but they're always brutal.

31:30.722 --> 31:33.141
So I need to make them strong.

31:33.141 --> 31:35.060
Hopefully they survive
the test.

31:35.060 --> 31:38.396
<i>What I'm gonna do is take</i>
<i>a piece of this mild steel</i>

31:38.396 --> 31:40.398
<i>and I'm gonna forge it out</i>
<i>into shape</i>

31:40.398 --> 31:43.193
<i>and then grind in a slot</i>
<i>for the high carbon bit.</i>

31:43.193 --> 31:45.237
<i>I really have to get</i>
<i>a good weld here.</i>

31:45.237 --> 31:47.322
I can't afford
to start all over again.

31:48.365 --> 31:50.367
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:50.367 --> 31:52.244
‐ So it's day two.
The plan for today

31:52.244 --> 31:54.371
is to really fix those eyes,
and really get them

31:54.371 --> 31:56.998
<i>to the shape I want.</i>

31:56.998 --> 31:59.543
Ended up stretching way
too much material.

31:59.543 --> 32:01.878
<i>One of the eyes</i>
<i>ended up cracking.</i>

32:01.878 --> 32:05.090
<i>There's no saving these,</i>
<i>and I'm starting to panic.</i>

32:05.090 --> 32:08.009
I mean, I don't have a whole
lot of room right there.

32:08.009 --> 32:09.761
<i>At this point</i>
<i>I'm burning daylight.</i>

32:09.761 --> 32:13.431
I'm just gonna have to scrap it
and start over.

32:13.431 --> 32:15.100
<i>I'm gonna do the wrap method.</i>

32:15.100 --> 32:18.103
Basically take
a flat bar of steel

32:18.103 --> 32:21.940
<i>and wrap it around an eye</i>
<i>and have a carbon steel core</i>

32:21.940 --> 32:25.443
<i>running all the way through</i>
<i>instead of just a bit.</i>

32:25.443 --> 32:26.611
<i>I don't really feel</i>
<i>good about it,</i>

32:26.611 --> 32:28.446
<i>but I'm gonna</i>
<i>really power through</i>

32:28.446 --> 32:30.907
<i>and work as fast</i>
<i>and hard as possible.</i>

32:30.907 --> 32:33.952
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:33.952 --> 32:35.787
My forge welding went good.

32:35.787 --> 32:37.247
<i>I believe they're good enough</i>
<i>for heat treat.</i>

32:37.247 --> 32:40.125
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:40.125 --> 32:41.293
<i>And I feel like</i>
<i>the heat treat process</i>

32:41.293 --> 32:42.794
<i>went really well,</i>

32:42.794 --> 32:45.255
<i>so next two days</i>
<i>I can focus on fit and finish.</i>

32:46.256 --> 32:47.632
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:47.632 --> 32:48.967
<i>‐ It's the morning</i>
<i>of day three.</i>

32:48.967 --> 32:50.844
<i>I still got a little more</i>
<i>forging to do.</i>

32:50.844 --> 32:53.138
<i>Steel's nice and hot.</i>
<i>Give it a couple of whacks.</i>

32:53.138 --> 32:54.973
<i>And it's feeling good already.</i>

32:54.973 --> 32:56.641
I'm, like, 99% sure

32:56.641 --> 32:58.101
<i>I have good forge weld.</i>

32:58.101 --> 32:59.311
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:59.311 --> 33:00.770
Go straight into the oil.

33:00.770 --> 33:03.273
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:03.273 --> 33:05.066
Oh, yeah.

33:05.066 --> 33:06.985
Art.

33:06.985 --> 33:09.988
<i>Axes have to have a handle,</i>
<i>so I cut out the hickory.</i>

33:09.988 --> 33:12.157
<i>Now it's time to shape 'em.</i>

33:12.157 --> 33:15.660
<i>I can feel the sawdust</i>
<i>adhering to my cheeks.</i>

33:15.660 --> 33:19.831
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:19.831 --> 33:21.166
<i>‐ So it's the morning</i>
<i>of day four.</i>

33:21.166 --> 33:23.001
<i>Today I'm gonna play dress up.</i>

33:23.001 --> 33:24.836
<i>These axes right now</i>
<i>are assembled.</i>

33:24.836 --> 33:27.422
<i>And I'm going to do</i>
<i>some finer detail work.</i>

33:31.009 --> 33:32.844
<i>So they both have</i>
<i>the finish that I want.</i>

33:32.844 --> 33:34.387
<i>Now I need to go above</i>
<i>and beyond.</i>

33:34.387 --> 33:36.014
<i>That's what my mom</i>
<i>would have wanted me to do.</i>

33:36.014 --> 33:37.432
<i>This was a challenge</i>

33:37.432 --> 33:39.976
and I'm really proud
that I pulled it off.

33:39.976 --> 33:45.523
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:45.523 --> 33:48.026
‐ Justin, Nic, welcome back
to The Forge.

33:48.026 --> 33:50.779
You dudes have had four days
at your home forges

33:50.779 --> 33:52.989
to finish those
Frankish throwing axes.

33:52.989 --> 33:55.200
Justin, tell the judges
about your blades.

33:55.200 --> 33:56.868
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:56.868 --> 34:00.372
<i>‐ So my axes are made out</i>
<i>of mild steel and 80CrV2</i>

34:00.372 --> 34:02.165
<i>for the bit</i>
<i>that's forge welded in there.</i>

34:02.165 --> 34:04.834
<i>And hickory for the handle.</i>

34:04.834 --> 34:06.753
‐ All right. Nic, how'd it go?

34:06.753 --> 34:09.464
‐ All in all, pretty good.

34:09.464 --> 34:11.716
<i>The blades itself</i>
<i>are mild steel construction</i>

34:11.716 --> 34:15.262
<i>with a 1095 core</i>
<i>and a charred hickory handle.</i>

34:15.262 --> 34:16.888
‐ All right, all right.

34:16.888 --> 34:19.849
To determine which of you is
our "Forged in Fire" champion,

34:19.849 --> 34:22.269
we're now gonna put your blades
through three tests.

34:22.269 --> 34:24.938
There will be a strength test,
a sharpness test, and up first,

34:24.938 --> 34:26.273
Doug's KEAL test.

34:26.273 --> 34:30.068
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:30.068 --> 34:31.736
‐ All right, bladesmiths.
Well, frankly,

34:31.736 --> 34:34.572
your Frankish throwing axes
look fantastic,

34:34.572 --> 34:35.907
but are they are lethal?

34:35.907 --> 34:37.200
Well, to find that out,

34:37.200 --> 34:39.744
I will take your weapons
and deliver some,

34:39.744 --> 34:43.081
well, hellish of a blow
on this ballistics dummy.

34:43.081 --> 34:44.916
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:44.916 --> 34:46.418
Justin, you're up first.
Are you ready?

34:46.418 --> 34:48.211
Let's wet it to the teeth.

34:48.211 --> 34:51.381
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:51.381 --> 34:53.591
I like going first. It takes
some of the pressure off,

34:53.591 --> 34:55.176
I think, because I don't
really care how Nic does.

34:55.176 --> 34:57.095
I'm here to see how I do.

34:57.095 --> 34:58.805
<i>I think if something</i>
<i>went wrong with the blades,</i>

34:58.805 --> 35:00.599
<i>it'd be the half Franken.</i>

35:00.599 --> 35:02.267
<i>There's not a lot of material</i>
<i>up there near the eye,</i>

35:02.267 --> 35:04.811
so I think that could be
